      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Regarding the lactose (lac) operon in bacteria, which of the following statements is accurate?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8882733",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30448,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. C. Contain regulatory genes, an operator gene, three structural genes and a promoter site.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Operon</strong> is a unit of <strong>gene expression</strong>. It includes <strong>structural genes</strong>, <strong>control elements</strong>, regulator/inhibitor gene, promoter, and operator areas, e.g., <strong>Lac operon</strong>.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/06/picture8_7dnvrf3.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"350\" height=\"158\"></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>A. Contains three structural genes:</strong> While <strong>true</strong>, this option is incomplete as it doesn't mention other critical components of the lac operon.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>B. Contains operator region:</strong> This is also <strong>correct</strong> but incomplete, as the lac operon includes more than just an operator region.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>D. Contains three structural genes, an operator, and a regulatory gene:</strong> This option is <strong>partially correct</strong> but lacks the mention of the promoter site and implies the regulatory gene is part of the operon, whereas it is usually located elsewhere on the chromosome.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The <strong>lac operon</strong> is a well-studied example of a <strong>gene regulatory system</strong> and includes <strong>three structural genes</strong> (lacZ, lacY, and lacA) that are involved in <strong>lactose metabolism</strong>. It also has a <strong>promoter site</strong> where <strong>RNA polymerase binds to initiate transcription</strong>, an <strong>operator site</strong> where the <strong>lac repressor can bind</strong> to <strong>inhibit transcription</strong>, and <strong>regulatory genes</strong> (such as the lacI gene that codes for the lac repressor protein) that control the operon's expression.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 636</strong></span></p>",
