      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">When initiating transcription of the lac operon, RNA polymerase first binds to which specific region?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1379955",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30449,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D. Promoter site</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Operon </strong>is a unit of <strong>gene expression </strong>which includes <strong>structural genes</strong>, <strong>control elements</strong>, <strong>regulator/inhibitor gene</strong>, promoter and operator areas, e.g. <strong>Lac operon</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In the <strong>bacterial cell</strong>, the <strong>Z gene</strong> encodes for <strong>beta-galactosidase</strong>, the enzyme that hydrolyses lactose to galactose and glucose.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>Y gene</strong> is responsible for <strong>production of a permease </strong>that <strong>transports lactose </strong>and <strong>galactose into the cell</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>A gene</strong> <strong>codes </strong>for <strong>thiogalactoside transacetylase.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/06/picture7_ZFVBJAo.jpg\" style=\"height:165px; width:350px\" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Since Z, Y and A code for the structure of the proteins, they are called <strong>structural genes</strong>, present as contiguous segments of DNA </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The transcription of these genes start from a common <strong>promoter </strong>(P), located close to the Z gene. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>RNA polymerase binds to the promoter </strong>&rarr;transcribes these three structural genes as a single mRNA.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A: </span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Transcription of the structural gene</strong> is under the control of another <strong>regulator </strong>or the &ldquo;i&rdquo; (<strong>inhibitor</strong>) gene, which is far away from the <strong>structural genes</strong>. <strong>Regulatory gene </strong>produces a <strong>repressor </strong>molecule.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Lac Y and Z gene:</strong> Encodes for enzymes.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C: </span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In the <strong>presence of glucose</strong> in the <strong>growth medium</strong>, the repressor is attached to the <strong>operator site</strong> and RNAP cannot move further. Thus, structural genes are not transcribed.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>RNA polymerase</strong> binds to the <strong>promoter site</strong> of the <strong>lac operon</strong> to <strong>initiate transcription.</strong> The <strong>promoter region</strong> is a <strong>sequence of DNA upstream</strong> of the <strong>structural genes</strong> that provides a <strong>binding site for RNA polymerase</strong> to start the <strong>transcription process</strong>. The promoter functions as the critical regulatory element for the initiation of gene transcription.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 636.</span></span></strong></p>",
